# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 PART A Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1: [KTU University Exam - June 2024]

**Q: Define MapReduce. List its two main functions and explain their roles in the Word Count program.**

**Model Answer:**

**MapReduce** is a distributed parallel processing programming model used by Hadoop to process vast amounts of data across clusters of commodity computers.

The two main user-defined functions are:

1. **Mapper Function**: Reads input splits line-by-line, tokenizes the text into individual words, and emits intermediate key-value pairs. In the Word Count program, the Mapper checks if each token matches a target keyword and, if so, emits `(keyword, 1)`.

2. **Reducer Function**: Receives all the intermediate values grouped by key (i.e., all the `1`s for a particular keyword) and aggregates them. In the Word Count program, the Reducer sums up all the `1`s to produce the final count `(keyword, total_count)`.

> [!NOTE]
> The Shuffle & Sort phase between Mapper and Reducer is framework-controlled and not user-defined.

---

### Question 2: [KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]

**Q: What is a Combiner in MapReduce? Why is it called an optional optimization?**

**Model Answer:**

A **Combiner** is an optional local reducer that runs on the Mapper node immediately after the mapping phase. It performs preliminary aggregation of intermediate key-value pairs *before* they are shuffled across the network to the Reducers.

For example, if a Mapper emits `(hadoop, 1)` five times locally, the Combiner pre-aggregates this to `(hadoop, 5)`, reducing the data sent over the network from 5 records to 1.

**Why "optional optimization"?**
- It is not always semantically correct to use a Combiner. The aggregation operation must be **associative and commutative** (e.g., SUM, MAX, MIN). For example, computing an AVERAGE cannot use a Combiner because averaging averages is mathematically incorrect.
- The framework does not guarantee that the Combiner will be executed — it is the developer's choice to enable it in the Driver class.

