### QUESTION B (14 Marks) — Alternative Choice

#### Part (a) — 7 Marks: [KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]

**Q: Differentiate between Hadoop MapReduce (Java) and Apache Spark. Why is MapReduce still preferred for batch processing of petabyte-scale data despite Spark's in-memory speed advantage?**

**Model Solution:**

| Feature | Hadoop MapReduce | Apache Spark |
|---|---|---|
| **Processing Model** | Disk-based (writes intermediate results to HDFS between stages) | In-memory (keeps data in RAM between stages) |
| **Speed** | Slower (I/O bottleneck) | Up to 100x faster for iterative jobs |
| **Ease of Coding** | Verbose Java code | Concise Python/Scala APIs |
| **Cost** | Lower (uses disk, cheaper hardware) | Higher (requires more RAM) |
| **Fault Tolerance** | Replication via HDFS (3x by default) | Lineage-based recomputation |
| **Best Suited For** | Batch processing, petabyte-scale linear jobs | Iterative ML, stream processing, graph processing |
| **Latency** | High (minutes to hours) | Low (seconds to minutes) |
| **Resource Manager** | YARN | YARN, Mesos, or Standalone |

**Why MapReduce is still preferred for petabyte-scale batch jobs:**

1. **Cost-Effectiveness at Scale**: MapReduce uses local disk for intermediate data, requiring cheaper hardware. Spark's in-memory model becomes prohibitively expensive at petabyte scale.

2. **Linear Processing Pipelines**: For non-iterative, one-pass aggregations (like our word count), MapReduce's overhead is minimal and the disk I/O is not a bottleneck.

3. **Mature Ecosystem**: MapReduce has been battle-tested in production for over a decade at companies like Yahoo, Facebook, and Twitter.

4. **Predictable Resource Usage**: MapReduce has a fixed memory footprint per task. Spark's in-memory caching can lead to OOM (Out-Of-Memory) errors on massive datasets.

5. **No Lineage Recomputation Cost**: If a Spark executor fails, it must recompute the entire RDD lineage (which can cascade). MapReduce simply re-runs the failed task on a different node.

