# Section 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

In the context of the **Apache Hadoop MapReduce** distributed computing framework, the experiment *"Calculate the average word length of all words starting with each character"* is a **word-frequency-style aggregation problem** that requires:

1. **Tokenization** of a large text corpus (stored in HDFS) into individual words.
2. **Grouping** of all words by their *first alphabetic character* (the key, ranging from `A` to `Z`).
3. **Aggregation** in the Reducer phase to compute the **arithmetic mean** of the word lengths belonging to each character group.

Formally, for every character $c \in \{A, B, C, \ldots, Z\}$ (case-insensitive), the program must compute:

$$\text{AvgLen}(c) = \frac{1}{N_c} \sum_{i=1}^{N_c} \vert W_i^{(c)} \vert$$

where $N_c$ is the number of words in the input that begin with character $c$, and $\vert W_i^{(c)} \vert$ denotes the length (number of characters) of the $i$-th such word. The MapReduce job is therefore a **secondary-sort-free, associative-aggregation** problem that is a textbook example of distributed text analytics.

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Syllabus Mapping (PCCDL508 – Module 2):** This experiment falls under *"MapReduce Programming Model – Aggregation & Statistical Analytics"*. It tests the learner's ability to design custom `Mapper`, `Reducer`, and `Driver` classes in Java using the `org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce` API.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy – The "Bucket Sorting Classroom" Intuition

Imagine an enormous classroom with **1 million students** (think of them as the *words in your dataset*) and **26 labelled buckets** labelled `A` to `Z` (the *first character*). A teacher (the **Mapper**) walks down the rows, looks at the first letter of each student's name, and drops a slip of paper into the correct bucket. Each slip notes the **length of the name** — not the name itself.

Once everyone is done, a counter (the **Reducer**) goes to each bucket, adds up all the lengths written on the slips, and divides by the number of slips. The result — *"the average name length starting with A is 5.4 characters"* — is written on the bucket. This is **exactly** what our Hadoop program does, but with words instead of student names and across a distributed cluster of machines.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Key Distinction from Word Count:** Unlike the classic Word Count experiment, this problem requires an *aggregate statistic* (mean). This means the Reducer must keep a **running sum** and a **running count** simultaneously, and only emit a single output line per character after processing the entire value group.

## 1.3 Standard Metrics & Conventions Used

| Term | Symbol | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| Input Split | $S$ | A block of HDFS data (default 128 MB) processed by one Mapper |
| Key Type | $K$ | First character of each word (Hadoop `Text`) |
| Value Type | $V$ | Length of each word (Hadoop `IntWritable`) |
| Character Group Cardinality | $N_c$ | Number of words beginning with character $c$ |
| Average Word Length | $\mu_c$ | $\mu_c = \frac{\sum \text{lengths}}{N_c}$ |
| **Default Block Size** | **128 MB** | Standard HDFS block size for Hadoop 3.x |
| **Replication Factor** | **3** | Default number of copies of each HDFS block |

