# Section 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 The MapReduce Programming Paradigm

Hadoop MapReduce operates in **two primary phases** separated by an implicit shuffle-and-sort phase:

1. **Map Phase** — The `Mapper` class's `map()` method is invoked once per `(key, value)` record. The input is typically a `(line_offset, line_text)` pair for a text file. The mapper emits zero or more **intermediate** `(key, value)` pairs.
2. **Shuffle & Sort Phase** — Hadoop's framework automatically groups all values belonging to the same key and routes them to a single Reducer.
3. **Reduce Phase** — The `Reducer` class's `reduce()` method receives a key and an **iterable** of all values associated with that key. It emits the final `(key, value)` output back to HDFS.

### 2.1.1 Why MapReduce Is the Right Tool

A naïve single-threaded program would need to:
- Load the entire text file into memory.
- Maintain 26 running sums and 26 running counts.
- Iterate through every word.

This breaks down when files reach the **terabyte scale** because the data no longer fits in RAM and there is no fault tolerance. MapReduce solves both problems by **partitioning** the work across a cluster and **streaming** the data through mapper tasks in parallel.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Distributed Computing Insight:** If we have a 1 TB input file on a 10-node cluster, each Mapper processes roughly **128 GB** of data. The 26 character groups are distributed across Reducers (one or more characters per Reducer) by the `Partitioner` class, ensuring parallel reduction.

## 2.2 Algorithm Design – Step-by-Step Logic

### Step 1: Input Reading
The `TextInputFormat` (default) reads the input file line by line. The Mapper receives:
- `key` = `LongWritable` (byte offset of the line in the file).
- `value` = `Text` (the actual line content).

### Step 2: Tokenization (Map Phase)
Each line is split into words using a `StringTokenizer` or `String.split("\\s+")`. Punctuation is stripped using a **regular expression** to ensure "Hello," and "Hello" are treated as the same word.

### Step 3: Key Extraction
For each clean word $w$:
- Let $c = w[0]$ be the first character.
- Convert $c$ to **uppercase** to make the analysis case-insensitive.
- Let $L = w.\text{length}()$ be the word length.

The mapper emits: $(\text{Text}(c),\; \text{IntWritable}(L))$.

### Step 4: Shuffle & Sort
Hadoop automatically:
- **Partitions** keys using `HashPartitioner` (default — hashes the key mod number of reducers).
- **Sorts** keys lexicographically (so output will be in `A, B, C, ... Z` order).
- **Groups** all values for the same key into an `Iterable<IntWritable>`.

### Step 5: Aggregation (Reduce Phase)
For each character key $c$, the reducer iterates through the iterable, maintaining:
- `sumLengths` $= \sum_{i=1}^{N_c} L_i$
- `count` $= N_c$

It then computes the **floating-point average**:

$$\mu_c = \frac{\text{sumLengths}}{\text{count}}$$

and writes a final output record: $(\text{Text}(c),\; \text{Text}(\mu_c))$.

## 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

> [!NOTE]
> The following table consolidates **every formula, parameter, and decision rule** you need for the KTU lab exam viva and record.

| # | Concept | Formula / Rule | Notes / Units |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | **Average word length for char $c$** | $\mu_c = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N_c} L_i}{N_c}$ | Unit: *characters per word* |
| 2 | **Sum of word lengths** | $S_c = \sum_{i=1}^{N_c} L_i$ | Integer (sum of `IntWritable`s) |
| 3 | **Number of words for char $c$** | $N_c = \vert \text{Group}(c) \vert$ | Count of iterable items |
| 4 | **Edge case – empty input** | If $N_c = 0$, then $\mu_c = 0$ | Always guard against divide-by-zero |
| 5 | **Tokenizer separator** | `\\s+` or `" \t\n\r\f"` | Regex for whitespace |
| 6 | **Punctuation strip regex** | `[^a-zA-Z]` | Removes non-alphabetic characters |
| 7 | **Default Hadoop block size** | **128 MB** (Hadoop 3.x) | Configurable via `dfs.blocksize` |
| 8 | **Replication factor** | **3** | Configurable via `dfs.replication` |
| 9 | **Output key type** | `org.apache.hadoop.io.Text` | UTF-8 string |
| 10 | **Output value type** | `org.apache.hadoop.io.Text` (formatted) or `DoubleWritable` | For floating-point mean |
| 11 | **Number of Reduce tasks** | Set via `job.setNumReduceTasks(n)` | $1 \le n \le 26$ typically |
| 12 | **Map-side combiner** | $\text{combine}(c, [L_1, L_2]) = (c, L_1 + L_2)$ | Reduces shuffle traffic |
| 13 | **WAL – Word-And-Length emission** | $(\text{char},\; \text{length})$ | Per-token intermediate pair |

## 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

This exact pattern — **group-by-key + arithmetic mean** — is used in industry for:

- **Log Analytics:** Average HTTP request size grouped by HTTP status code class (2xx, 3xx, 4xx, 5xx).
- **Bioinformatics:** Average gene length grouped by the starting nucleotide (A, T, G, C).
- **Search Engine Indexing:** Average document length grouped by first-letter prefix for autocomplete optimization.
- **Social Media Analytics:** Average tweet length grouped by hashtag first character for trend analysis.
- **NLP Feature Engineering:** Computing character-level features for text classification models.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Interview Pearl:** This experiment is the canonical example used by companies (Amazon, Flipkart, Mu Sigma) in Hadoop interviews. Mastering it demonstrates strong understanding of the **"emit-then-aggregate"** pattern that powers virtually all MapReduce jobs.

