#### Model Solution for Q (b) — 7 Marks

**Part 1: Role of Partitioner** (2 marks)

The `Partitioner` class determines **which Reducer** receives a given intermediate `(key, value)` pair. Hadoop's default `HashPartitioner` computes `partition = (key.hashCode() & Integer.MAX_VALUE) % numReduceTasks`. For our program, this means that all pairs for character `'A'` may go to Reducer #2, all for `'M'` to Reducer #5, etc. **Without partitioning, all data would go to a single Reducer, defeating the purpose of distributed processing.**

**Part 2: Role of Combiner** (2 marks)

The `Combiner` is a *mini-Reducer* that runs **locally on the Mapper node** after the map output is finalized but **before** the data is shuffled to Reducers. It performs **local aggregation** to reduce the volume of network traffic. For our program, if a single Mapper emits `(H,6), (H,5), (H,2)`, a combiner can pre-sum these to `(H,13)` (assuming we use a sum-only combiner) or even `(H,13,3)` with a custom Writable. The benefit: instead of transferring 3 records, only 1 is sent.

**Part 3: Effect of `setNumReduceTasks(0)`** (3 marks)

Setting `job.setNumReduceTasks(0)` instructs Hadoop to **skip the Reduce phase entirely**. The Map output is written **directly** to HDFS as the final output, with each Mapper producing one output file (`part-m-00000`, `part-m-00001`, etc.). For our experiment, this would be **catastrophic** because:

- Each line of the input would produce a separate output file like `(H, 6)`, `(H, 5)`, `(I, 2)`, `(G, 5)`, etc.
- **No aggregation would occur** — the averaging computation requires grouping all values for the same key, which only happens in the Reducer.
- The output would be useless for the purpose of the experiment (we would get raw emissions, not averages).

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout:**
> 1. **Common Mistake 1:** Forgetting to override the **intermediate output types** (`setMapOutputKeyClass` and `setMapOutputValueClass`). The Mapper outputs `Text, IntWritable`, but the final output is `Text, Text`. If you only set the final output types, Hadoop throws a `ClassCastException` at runtime. **Loss: 1 mark.**
> 2. **Common Mistake 2:** Iterating through `Iterable<IntWritable> values` **more than once** in the Reducer. Hadoop reuses the same object for every value in the iterable to save memory. Iterating twice will give you the same final value repeated! **Loss: 2 marks.**
> 3. **Common Mistake 3:** Using `int sum` instead of `long sum`. For inputs larger than ~2 billion characters (a 1 GB text file can hit this), the integer overflows and produces wrong averages. **Loss: 1 mark.**
> 4. **Common Mistake 4:** Not stripping punctuation. The words `"Hello,"` and `"Hello"` would be counted as different words, skewing the average. **Loss: 1 mark.**

